Gray Before Their Time
By ED HIRSCH
It is my convention that the “Grinnell
experience" is a logical exercise in
sending creativity as long as the educational system exists in its present
institutional form. It dress't take a
freshman long to learn the ways of life
in the Grinnell game. First of all there
is a professor who site operated at the
front of the classroom and then there
are students who sit below in next
rows, details deeply posted. The pmfessor then speaks. details begin to fly as
nearly of wisdom drop from the lead
er's mouth. Later there will be a test
and a certification that the student
“knows" the material 2.5 well or 3.0
or whatever his particular parents recommend.
After one year at Grinnell my immediate reaction is that the system or the
people within the system are in serious
need of change if education is to be
come relevant. As long as there is a
professor lodging a student by handling a grade over his head (Grinnell
terms put it more humanity) there can
be little real communication between
professor and student. This system has
been indoctrinated as the best of all possible worlds so well that students actually believe education consists of
decorating the professor's concepts
and applying them to his general ques-
 
