COAST-TO-COAST
Human Biology Seminar — A New Approach
By RON STEINHORN
The seminar in human biology was
first created by Sheldon garden to be
a new Approach in teaching various
topics in biology. This year's Science I
sequence for example was based around
the general theme ”evolution ot start»
sure," and had been less than successful in crossing interest, a: have all the
introductory biology sequences tried here
during the past several years. In contest, the idea of the human biology
course is to organize the traditional
topics or biology; genetics, immunology.
anatomy, physiology. ecology, evolution,
microbiology, and others around their
presence in the human being. The great
advantage at this presentation in an introductory biology course is that interest
can be easily created since the application of biological ideas to the students themselves is always at the more
front. For the non-bio—major' in particular
this is useful, because only in this way
is knowledge of tile subject likely to be
useful to them in the future.
To see whether this would be a good
way oi organizing a future course, this
past semester about twelve seniors and
seniors participated in what was Called
the "human biology seminar," which
met with the gardens every week at
their home. Not everyone in the seminar
was a biologist. One was in psychology
and another in American Studies. As
time went on, it became obvious that
these different perspectives on the human being were extremely important for
the group.
At the plant, the group made a plan of
topics to be covered The general format.
01 a session was that one or several per:
pre would report on certain of the select-
» ed topics. This worked out so that each
person reported every three or four
weeks. The presentations always pro.
solved much discussion and reaction and
the seminar invariably listed for about
three hours each time as the result of
the reaction the reports provided This
more out the initial feeling that it would
not be necessary for everybody to pre‘
page material or read for all the sessions, since most of the members had
background! extensive enough so that
the innovation was not without reference to subjects previously studied.
it is site to say that everyone who was
in the seminar tell it was a great sun<
less. Those who had a lot of biological training before saw new aspects and
applications of areas previously studied
while the non-biological felt, perhaps
for the first time, the means and extent
to which biological licenses influence
and control our lives These factors,
along with the intense discussion and ex<
movement which were always present and
which are the mark of any meaningful
learning experience make a course in
human biology seem a real alternative
to traditional ways of biological teaching.
 
